37:52.537 --> 37:58.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. RAPHAEL MECHOULAM: And I was
kind of surprised
to find out that the chemistry
of cannabis,

37:58.143 --> 38:06.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an important drug, in my view,
wasn't well-known.
As a matter of fact, we didn't
know at that

38:06.184 --> 38:11.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time -- I'm speaking of the
early '60s -- the
active compounds had not been
isolated in

38:11.089 --> 38:12.790 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pure form.

38:12.824 --> 38:18.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In 1963, he
identified the
structure of cannabidiol, CBD,
one of the

38:18.363 --> 38:25.303 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
most medically important
compounds found in
cannabis, and, in 1964, he
isolated the active

38:25.336 --> 38:28.006 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
component of marijuana,
tetrahydrocannabinol,
THC.

38:28.039 --> 38:35.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. RAPHAEL MECHOULAM: I thought
that as soon
as we know the chemistry and the
pharmacology

38:35.113 --> 38:40.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then the toxicity, and if
there are any
positive effects, companies will
go in and

38:40.485 --> 38:48.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
take compounds and go ahead with
clinical
trials, which is true for a
huge, huge number

38:48.726 --> 38:50.528 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
